aws::graph::propositions: # Cessna 182G Aircraft Accident Information
The aircraft experienced an aerodynamic stall/spin during takeoff.
The aircraft entered an uncontrolled descent.
The aircraft collided with terrain/object (non-CFIT).
The pilot held a Private certificate.
The pilot was 66 years old.
The pilot had Single-engine land airplane rating.
The pilot occupied the left seat.
The pilot had no other aircraft ratings.
The pilot used a 3-point restraint.
The pilot had no instrument rating.
No second pilot was present.
The pilot had no instructor rating.
No toxicology was performed on the pilot.
The pilot held Class 3 medical certification with waivers/limitations.
The pilot's last FAA medical exam was on May 28, 2014.
The pilot was not an occupational pilot.
The pilot's last flight review or equivalent was on September 20, 2014.
The pilot had 471.2 total flight hours in all aircraft.
The pilot had 248.8 total flight hours in this make and model.
The pilot had 349.3 Pilot In Command hours in all aircraft.
The pilot had 14.6 flight hours in the last 90 days in all aircraft.
The pilot had 14.6 flight hours in the last 30 days in all aircraft.
The aircraft was a Cessna 182G.
The aircraft registration was N2309R.
The aircraft model/series was 182G G.
The aircraft category was Airplane.
The aircraft year of manufacture was 1964.
The aircraft was not amateur built.
The aircraft had a Normal airworthiness certificate.
The aircraft serial number was 18255409.
The aircraft had tricycle landing gear.
The aircraft had 4 seats.
The aircraft's last inspection was an Annual on September 25, 2014.
The aircraft's certified maximum gross weight was 2348 lbs.
The aircraft had 1 reciprocating engine.
The aircraft's airframe total time was 5566.1 hours at time of accident.
The engine manufacturer was Continental Motor.
The aircraft had an ELT installed and activated, but it did not aid in locating the accident.
The engine model/series was O-470-R.
The engine was rated at 230 Horsepower.
